<TITLE>Rally for Muslims could draw thousands to Copley Square on Sunday</TITLE>
<TEXT>
Thousands have said they plan to support Muslim Americans and demonstrate in Copley Square Sunday afternoon in opposition to Presdent Trump’s immigration order. 

The Massachusetts chapter of the Council on American Islamic Relations (CAIR), a Muslim civil rights organization, will host a rally at 1 p.m., according to a statement on the group’s website. , more than 12,000 people were planning to attend as of Saturday night, with another 23,000 people expressing interest in going. 


The Copley Square protest is one of many demonstrations across the country in response to Trump’s executive order, which he signed on Friday. Trump’s order puts a 90 day restriction on immigration from seven countries with predominatley Muslim populations — Iraq, Syria, Iran, Libya, Somalia, Sudan and Yemen. The order also bans the admission for refugees for 120 days, and indefinitely suspends the admission of Syrian refugees.

Those in favor of Trump’s order , stricter vetting is a positive step toward trying to make the country safer. Late on Saturday, , preventing the government from deporting them. 

On Saturday night, at airports in New York, Chicago and Boston, protesters demanded the release of any travelers being detained as a result of Trump’s order. At Logan International Airport on Saturday night, crowds were joined by local officials, including US Senator Elizabeth Warren, City Councilor Tito Jackson and Mayor Martin J. Walsh to denounce the immigration ban.

Warren told protesters, “We will not turn away people who try to help Americans. We will not turn away anyone because of their religion.”

Earlier on Saturday, hundreds rallied in Chinatown and marched toward the State House.Sunday’s rally will take place at the Khalil Gibran Plaque. Gibran, a poet, was an immigrant from Lebanon who wrote and illustrated “The Prophet.” 

The rally will also include a Muslim prayer at 2:30 p.m., and CAIR says all are encouraged to attend. 

CAIR’s stated mission is “to enhance the understanding of Islam, encourage dialogue, protect civil liberties, empower American Muslims, and build coalitions that promote social justice and mutual understanding.”
